	(6,'Rhinoart::Page',1,'create',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-02-18 09:03:15'),
	(7,'Rhinoart::PageContent',1,'update','1','---\nid: 1\npage_id: 1\nname: main_content\ncontent: <p>Simple text for index page</p>\nposition: 1\n',NULL,'2015-02-18 09:27:32'),
	(8,'Rhinoart::PageContent',1,'update','1','---\nid: 1\npage_id: 1\nname: main_content\ncontent: ! \"Simple text for index page\\r\\n\"\nposition: 1\n',NULL,'2015-02-18 09:28:05'),
	(9,'Rhinoart::PageContent',1,'update','1','---\nid: 1\npage_id: 1\nname: main_content\ncontent: ! \'&lt;h1&gt;Simple text for index page&lt;/h1&gt;\'\nposition: 1\n',NULL,'2015-02-18 09:28:21'),
	(10,'Rhinoart::PageContent',2,'create','1',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-18 09:28:40'),
	(11,'Rhinoart::PageContent',2,'update','1','---\nid: 2\npage_id: 1\nname: head\ncontent: \'\'\nposition: 2\n',NULL,'2015-02-18 09:32:29'),
	(12,'Rhinoart::PageContent',1,'update','1','---\nid: 1\npage_id: 1\nname: main_content\ncontent: ! \"\\t<section id=\\\"definition\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"row\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><h2>Definition</h2></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Osteoarthritis</strong> is the most\n  common cause of musculoskeletal pain and disability in the knee joint. In the knee\n  joint, the end of the femur (thigh bone) and tibia (shin bone) are covered in smooth\n  articulate cartilage. Between the two bones sits a second type of cartilage, called\n  menisci, which act as cartilage shock absorber pads. Joint fluid also adds lubrication\n  to the knee joint.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img src=\\\"images/img01.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-left\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Osteoarthritis\n  (OA)</strong> starts as the lack or loss of this articulate (surface) cartilage\n  and then progresses into involvement with the surrounding bone, tissues, and synovial\n  fluid. In osteoarthritis, cartilage may have areas of partial thickness loss (thinning)\n  or complete loss of surface cartilage resulting in areas of exposed bone. Isolated\n  cartilage loss may be a result of isolated trauma or it may be a result of chronic\n  wear and tear of the joint.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\t\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t</section>\\r\\n\\t<section\n  id=\\\"prevalence\\\" class=\\\"gray\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"row\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><h2>Prevalence</h2></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>It has been estimated that 12% of Americans\n  aged >25 years have clinical signs and symptoms of OA. Further studies have shown\n  80% of people older than 75 have symptoms of OA, and cadaveric studies have shown\n  universal signs of arthritis in patients 65 and older. Studies have provided conflicting\n  evidence regarding activities and the development of osteoarthritis. While moderate\n  physical stress helps maintain the integrity of the surface cartilage, excessive\n  stress may result in cartilage degradation. </p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"row row-centered\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12 col-sm-9 col-centered\\\"><img\n  src=\\\"images/img11.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\"></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t</section>\\r\\n\\t<section\n  id=\\\"risk\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"row\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><h2>Risk Factors</h2></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Osteoarthritis\n  of the knee may happen as a result of injury or infection but often there is no\n  obvious precipitating cause. Some of the following risk factors may play a part\n  in the developing of osteoarthritis of the knee:</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img src=\\\"images/img02.png\\\"\n  alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-left\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Inherited genes.</strong>\n  This includes the possibility of genetic mutations that might make a person more\n  likely to develop osteoarthritis of the knee.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Age.</strong>\n  The ability of cartilage to heal decreases as a person gets older.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Gender.</strong>\n  Women who are 50 years old and over are more likely than men to develop osteoarthritis\n  of the knee.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Repetitive stress injuries.</strong> These\n  are usually a result of the type of job a person has. Certain occupations that include\n  a lot of walking (over 3.2km/2 miles per daya), kneeling, squatting or lifting heavy\n  weights (25kg/55lb or more) have higher incidences of osteoarthritis of the knee\n  because of the constant pressure on the joint.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Weight.</strong>\n  Body weight increases pressure on all the joints including the knees.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Athletics.</strong>\n  Athletes involved in football, tennis or long-distance running are at higher risk\n  of developing osteoarthritis of the knee.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Other illnesses.</strong>\n  This includes gout and certain metabolic disorders (diabetes mellitus, for example).</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t</section>\\r\\n\\t<section\n  id=\\\"symptoms\\\" class=\\\"gray\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"row\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><h2>Symptoms</h2></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12 col-sm-8\\\">\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>The main symptoms of osteoarthritis\n  of the knee are:</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>pain (particularly when\n  you’re moving your knee or at the end of the day – this usually gets better when\n  you rest)</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>stiffness (especially after rest – this usually\n  eases after a minute or so as you get moving)</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>crepitus,\n  a creaking, crunching, grinding sensation when you move the joint</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>hard\n  swellings (caused by osteophytes)</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>soft swellings (caused\n  by extra fluid in the joint).</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Other\n  symptoms can include: </p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>your knee giving\n  way because your muscles have become weak or the joint structure is less stable</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>your\n  knee not moving as freely or as far as normal</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>your knees\n  becoming bent and bowed</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>the muscles around your joint looking\n  thin or wasted.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>It’s unusual, but some people\n  have pain in their knee that wakes them up at night. This generally only happens\n  with severe osteoarthritis.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>You’ll probably find that your pain\n  will vary and that you have good days and bad days, sometimes depending on how active\n  you’ve been but sometimes for no clear reason.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Some people find\n  that changes in the weather (especially damp weather and low pressure) make their\n  pain and stiffness worse. This may be because nerve fibres in the capsule of their\n  knee are sensitive to changes in atmospheric pressure.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12 col-sm-4\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img src=\\\"images/img03.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img\n  src=\\\"images/img12.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t</section>\\r\\n\\t<section\n  id=\\\"diagnostic\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"row\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><h2>Diagnostic</h2></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<img\n  src=\\\"images/img04.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-right\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Your doctor\n  will make a diagnosis of osteoarthritis of the knee based on your symptoms and an\n  examination. During the examination, they’ll check for:</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>tenderness\n  over your knee</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>creaking and grating (crepitus)</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>bony\n  swelling</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>excess fluid</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>restricted\n  movement</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>instability of your knee</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>thinning\n  of the muscles that support your knee.</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img\n  src=\\\"images/img05.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-left\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<strong>What\n  tests are there for osteoarthritis of the knee?</strong>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>X-rays\n  are the most useful tests to confirm a diagnosis of osteoarthritis, although they\n  won’t often be needed. X-rays may show changes such as osteophytes, narrowing of\n  the space between bones and calcium deposits within your joint.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>X-rays\n  aren’t a good indicator of how much pain or disability you’re likely to have – some\n  people have a lot of pain from minor joint damage but others have little pain from\n  severe damage.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Your doctor may suggest you have a magnetic resonance\n  imaging (MRI) scan on your knee, which will show the soft tissues (e.g. cartilage,\n  tendons, muscles) and changes in the bone that can’t be seen on a standard x-ray.\n  This is quite rare though.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>There’s no blood test for osteoarthritis\n  but they can be used to rule out other conditions</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t</section>\\r\\n\\t<section\n  id=\\\"treatment\\\" class=\\\"gray\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"row\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><h2>Treatment</h2></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>There’s no cure for osteoarthritis as yet,\n  but there are a number of treatments that can help ease symptoms and reduce the\n  chances of your arthritis becoming worse.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img src=\\\"images/img06.png\\\"\n  alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-right\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<h3>Drugs for osteoarthritis of the\n  knee</h3>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Painkillers (analgesics)</strong> help with pain\n  and stiffness but they don’t affect the arthritis itself and won’t repair the damage\n  to your joint.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Painkillers are best used\n  occasionally when you’re in pain or when you’re likely to be exercising.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Paracetamol\n  is usually the best and most well-tolerated painkiller, but make sure you take the\n  right dose because many people take too little – try 1 g (usually 2 tablets) 3 or\n  4 times a day. You can buy them from your chemist or supermarket.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Combined\n  painkillers (e.g. co-codamol, co-dydramol) contain paracetamol and a second codeine-like\n  drug, so they may be helpful for more severe pain. Because they’re stronger than\n  painkillers, they’re more likely to cause side-effects such as dizziness and constipation.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Non-steroidal\n  anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs),</strong> for example ibuprofen or naproxen, may\n  be recommended if inflammation is contributing to your pain and stiffness.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>NSAIDs\n  can sometimes have side-effects, but your doctor will take precautions to reduce\n  the risk of these. They may suggest the lowest effective dose for the shortest possible\n  time and prescribe another drug called a proton pump inhibitor to help protect your\n  stomach from digestive problems.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>NSAIDs also carry a slightly\n  increased risk of a heart attack or stroke, so your doctor will be cautious about\n  prescribing them if there are other factors that increase your overall risk (e.g.\n  you smoke or you have circulation problems, diabetes, high blood pressure or high\n  cholesterol).</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory\n  creams and gels are a good option if you have trouble taking NSAID tablets.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Creams\n  and gels can be applied directly onto painful joints three times a day and there’s\n  no need to rub them in – they absorb through your skin on their own.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>They’re\n  extremely well tolerated because very little is absorbed into your bloodstream.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>You\n  can tell within a few days whether they’ll help with your pain.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img\n  class=\\\"pull-left\\\" src=\\\"images/img12.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Capsaicin\n  cream</strong> is made from the pepper plant (capsicum) and is an effective and\n  well-tolerated painkiller.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Capsaicin cream\n  is only available on prescription and needs to be applied three times a day.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Most\n  people feel a warming or burning sensation when they first use it, but this generally\n  wears off after several days.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>The pain relief starts after\n  a few days and you should try it for at least two weeks before deciding if it’s\n  helped.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Stronger painkillers,</strong>\n  for example opioids/anti-inflammatories, may be prescribed if you have severe pain\n  and other medications don’t work well enough.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Stronger\n  painkillers are more likely to have side-effects, especially nausea, dizziness and\n  confusion, so you’ll need to see your doctor regularly and report any problems.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Some\n  opioids can be given as a plaster patch to wear on your skin, which can give pain\n  relief for a number of days.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Stronger painkillers are only\n  available on prescription.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Because these\n  treatments work in different ways, you can combine them for greater pain relief.\n  Ask your chemist or doctor for advice on safe combinations.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img\n  src=\\\"images/img07.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-right\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Steroid\n  injections</strong> are sometimes given directly into a particularly painful knee\n  joint.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>The injections can start working\n  within a day or so and may improve pain for several weeks or months.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>They’re\n  mainly used for very painful osteoarthritis, for sudden attacks caused by shedding\n  calcium crystals and to help you through important events (such as a family wedding).</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Arthritis\n  Research UK has awarded a grant for the PROMOTE trial, a study into whether methotrexate,\n  a drug commonly used to treat rheumatoid arthritis, can be used to treat osteoarthritis\n  of the knee. Another trial is looking into whether a drug called spironolactone\n  is an effective treatment.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>If you have trouble opening childproof\n  containers, ask the pharmacist to put your drugs in a more suitable container. You\n  can also order a child-resistant closure card.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<h3>Other treatment\n  options</h3>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Applying warmth or cold</strong> to your knee\n  can relieve pain and stiffness.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Heat lamps\n  are popular, but a hot-water bottle or reheatable pad (available from most chemists)\n  are just as effective.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>An ice pack can also ease pain.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Don’t\n  apply a hot or cold pad directly onto the skin.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Hyaluronic\n  acid injections,</strong> which help to lubricate your knee joint, are sometimes\n  given when steroid injections don’t work.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>You\n  may be given a single injection or a course of several injections.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>This\n  form of treatment isn’t approved by the National Institute for Health and Clinical\n  Excellence (NICE) and isn’t widely used because the evidence that it works isn’t\n  convincing.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img class=\\\"pull-left\\\" src=\\\"images/img08.png\\\"\n  alt=\\\"\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Transcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation (TENS),</strong>\n  can be used for pain relief, although research evidence suggests that it doesn’t\n  work for everyone.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>A TENS machine is a\n  small electronic device that sends pulses to the nerve endings via pads placed on\n  the skin. The device produces a tingling sensation which is thought to modify the\n  pain messages sent to the brain.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>TENS machines are available\n  from pharmacies and other major stores, but a physiotherapist may be able to loan\n  you one to try before you decide to buy one.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Knee\n  braces</strong> are becoming more popular and more evidence to support their use\n  for osteoarthritis is emerging.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>There are\n  several types that can help to stabilise the kneecap and make it move correctly.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>You\n  can buy knee braces from sports shops and chemists, but you should speak to your\n  doctor or physiotherapist first. They may also be able to provide braces or recommend\n  the best ones for you.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Surgery</strong>\n  may be recommended if you have severe pain or mobility problems.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<h3>Surgery</h3>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>In\n  cases of advanced OA where surgery is called for, patients may also see a physical\n  therapist before surgery to discuss exercises that will be used just after surgery\n  and to begin practicing using crutches or a walker.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img src=\\\"images/img09.png\\\"\n  alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-left\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<strong>Arthroscopy</strong>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Surgeons\n  can use an arthroscope (mentioned earlier) to check the condition of the articular\n  cartilage. They can also clean the joint by removing loose fragments of cartilage.\n  People have reported relief when doctors simply flush the joint with saline solution.\n  A burring tool may be used to roughen spots on the cartilage that are badly worn.\n  This promotes growth of new cartilage called fibrocartilage, which is like scar\n  tissue. This procedure is often helpful for temporary relief of symptoms for up\n  to two years.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<strong>Proximal Tibial Osteotomy</strong>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>OA\n  usually affects the side of the knee closest to the other knee (called the medial\n  compartment) more often than the outside part (the lateral compartment). OA in the\n  medial compartment can lead to bowing of the knee. As mentioned earlier, a bowlegged\n  posture places more pressure than normal on the medial compartment. The added pressure\n  leads to more pain and faster degeneration where the cartilage is being squeezed\n  together.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Surgery to realign the angles in the lower leg can\n  help shift pressure to the other, healthier side of the knee. The goal is to reduce\n  the pain and delay further degeneration of the medial compartment.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>One\n  procedure to realign the angles of the lower leg is called a proximal tibial osteotomy.\n  In this procedure, the upper (proximal)</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<strong>Artificial Knee\n  Replacement</strong>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>An artificial knee replacement is the ultimate\n  solution for advanced knee OA.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Surgeons prefer not to put a\n  new knee joint in patients younger than 60. This is because younger patients are\n  generally more active and might put too much stress on the joint, causing it to\n  loosen or even crack. A revision surgery to replace a damaged prosthesis is harder\n  to do, has more possible complications, and is usually less successful than a first-time\n  joint replacement surgery.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t</section>\\r\"\nposition: 1\n',NULL,'2015-02-18 11:10:16'),
	(13,'Rhinoart::PageContent',2,'update','1','---\nid: 2\npage_id: 1\nname: head\ncontent: ! \"\\t<header class=\\\"header\\\">\\r\\n\\t<h1 class=\\\"logo\\\"><a href=\\\"home.html\\\">Knee\n  Osteoarthritis</a></h1>\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"row row-centered\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<nav id=\\\"nav\\\" class=\\\"col-centered col-xs-12\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"navigation-block\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<span class=\\\"opener-nav\\\"></span>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul\n  class=\\\"navigation\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li class=\\\"active\\\"><a href=\\\"#definition\\\">Definition</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a\n  href=\\\"#prevalence\\\">Prevalence</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a href=\\\"#risk\\\">Risk\n  factors</a></li>\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a href=\\\"#symptoms\\\">Symptoms</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a\n  href=\\\"#diagnostic\\\">Diagnostic</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a href=\\\"#treatment\\\">Treatment</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</nav>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t</header>\\r\"\nposition: 2\n',NULL,'2015-02-18 11:10:16'),
	(14,'Rhinoart::PageContent',3,'update','1','---\nid: 3\npage_id: 1\nname: footer\ncontent: ! \"\\t<footer class=\\\"footer\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<nav id=\\\"fnav\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a\n  href=\\\"#definition\\\">Definition</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a href=\\\"#prevalence\\\">Prevalence</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a\n  href=\\\"#risk\\\">Risk factors</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a href=\\\"#symptoms\\\">Symptoms</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a\n  href=\\\"#diagnostic\\\">Diagnostic</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a href=\\\"#treatment\\\">Treatment</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t</nav>\\r\\n\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"row row-centered\\\">\\t\\t\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12 col-centered\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<nav class=\\\"social-nav\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a\n  href=\\\"#\\\"></a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li class=\\\"twitter\\\"><a href=\\\"#\\\"></a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li\n  class=\\\"google\\\"><a href=\\\"#\\\"></a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li class=\\\"youtube\\\"><a\n  href=\\\"#\\\"></a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li class=\\\"instagram\\\"><a href=\\\"#\\\"></a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</nav>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><span class=\\\"copy\\\">© 2014 Knee Osteoarthritis. All rights\n  reserved.</span></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t</footer>\\r\"\nposition: 3\n',NULL,'2015-02-18 11:10:16'),
	(15,'Rhinoart::PageContent',1,'update','1','---\nid: 1\npage_id: 1\nname: main_content\ncontent: ! \"<section id=\\\"definition\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"row\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><h2>Definition</h2></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Osteoarthritis</strong> is the most\n  common cause of musculoskeletal pain and disability in the knee joint. In the knee\n  joint, the end of the femur (thigh bone) and tibia (shin bone) are covered in smooth\n  articulate cartilage. Between the two bones sits a second type of cartilage, called\n  menisci, which act as cartilage shock absorber pads. Joint fluid also adds lubrication\n  to the knee joint.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img src=\\\"/uploads/images/img01.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\"\n  class=\\\"pull-left\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Osteoarthritis (OA)</strong> starts\n  as the lack or loss of this articulate (surface) cartilage and then progresses into\n  involvement with the surrounding bone, tissues, and synovial fluid. In osteoarthritis,\n  cartilage may have areas of partial thickness loss (thinning) or complete loss of\n  surface cartilage resulting in areas of exposed bone. Isolated cartilage loss may\n  be a result of isolated trauma or it may be a result of chronic wear and tear of\n  the joint.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\t\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t</section>\\r\\n\\t<section\n  id=\\\"prevalence\\\" class=\\\"gray\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"row\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><h2>Prevalence</h2></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>It has been estimated that 12% of Americans\n  aged >25 years have clinical signs and symptoms of OA. Further studies have shown\n  80% of people older than 75 have symptoms of OA, and cadaveric studies have shown\n  universal signs of arthritis in patients 65 and older. Studies have provided conflicting\n  evidence regarding activities and the development of osteoarthritis. While moderate\n  physical stress helps maintain the integrity of the surface cartilage, excessive\n  stress may result in cartilage degradation. </p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"row row-centered\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12 col-sm-9 col-centered\\\"><img\n  src=\\\"/uploads/images/img11.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\"></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t</section>\\r\\n\\t<section\n  id=\\\"risk\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"row\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><h2>Risk Factors</h2></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Osteoarthritis\n  of the knee may happen as a result of injury or infection but often there is no\n  obvious precipitating cause. Some of the following risk factors may play a part\n  in the developing of osteoarthritis of the knee:</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img src=\\\"/uploads/images/img02.png\\\"\n  alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-left\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Inherited genes.</strong>\n  This includes the possibility of genetic mutations that might make a person more\n  likely to develop osteoarthritis of the knee.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Age.</strong>\n  The ability of cartilage to heal decreases as a person gets older.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Gender.</strong>\n  Women who are 50 years old and over are more likely than men to develop osteoarthritis\n  of the knee.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Repetitive stress injuries.</strong> These\n  are usually a result of the type of job a person has. Certain occupations that include\n  a lot of walking (over 3.2km/2 miles per daya), kneeling, squatting or lifting heavy\n  weights (25kg/55lb or more) have higher incidences of osteoarthritis of the knee\n  because of the constant pressure on the joint.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Weight.</strong>\n  Body weight increases pressure on all the joints including the knees.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Athletics.</strong>\n  Athletes involved in football, tennis or long-distance running are at higher risk\n  of developing osteoarthritis of the knee.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Other illnesses.</strong>\n  This includes gout and certain metabolic disorders (diabetes mellitus, for example).</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t</section>\\r\\n\\t<section\n  id=\\\"symptoms\\\" class=\\\"gray\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"row\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><h2>Symptoms</h2></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12 col-sm-8\\\">\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>The main symptoms of osteoarthritis\n  of the knee are:</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>pain (particularly when\n  you’re moving your knee or at the end of the day – this usually gets better when\n  you rest)</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>stiffness (especially after rest – this usually\n  eases after a minute or so as you get moving)</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>crepitus,\n  a creaking, crunching, grinding sensation when you move the joint</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>hard\n  swellings (caused by osteophytes)</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>soft swellings (caused\n  by extra fluid in the joint).</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Other\n  symptoms can include: </p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>your knee giving\n  way because your muscles have become weak or the joint structure is less stable</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>your\n  knee not moving as freely or as far as normal</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>your knees\n  becoming bent and bowed</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>the muscles around your joint looking\n  thin or wasted.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>It’s unusual, but some people\n  have pain in their knee that wakes them up at night. This generally only happens\n  with severe osteoarthritis.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>You’ll probably find that your pain\n  will vary and that you have good days and bad days, sometimes depending on how active\n  you’ve been but sometimes for no clear reason.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Some people find\n  that changes in the weather (especially damp weather and low pressure) make their\n  pain and stiffness worse. This may be because nerve fibres in the capsule of their\n  knee are sensitive to changes in atmospheric pressure.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12 col-sm-4\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img src=\\\"/uploads/images/img03.png\\\"\n  alt=\\\"\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img src=\\\"/uploads/images/img12.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t</section>\\r\\n\\t<section\n  id=\\\"diagnostic\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"row\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><h2>Diagnostic</h2></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<img\n  src=\\\"/uploads/images/img04.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-right\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Your\n  doctor will make a diagnosis of osteoarthritis of the knee based on your symptoms\n  and an examination. During the examination, they’ll check for:</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>tenderness\n  over your knee</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>creaking and grating (crepitus)</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>bony\n  swelling</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>excess fluid</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>restricted\n  movement</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>instability of your knee</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><span>thinning\n  of the muscles that support your knee.</span></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img\n  src=\\\"/uploads/images/img05.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-left\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<strong>What\n  tests are there for osteoarthritis of the knee?</strong>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>X-rays\n  are the most useful tests to confirm a diagnosis of osteoarthritis, although they\n  won’t often be needed. X-rays may show changes such as osteophytes, narrowing of\n  the space between bones and calcium deposits within your joint.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>X-rays\n  aren’t a good indicator of how much pain or disability you’re likely to have – some\n  people have a lot of pain from minor joint damage but others have little pain from\n  severe damage.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Your doctor may suggest you have a magnetic resonance\n  imaging (MRI) scan on your knee, which will show the soft tissues (e.g. cartilage,\n  tendons, muscles) and changes in the bone that can’t be seen on a standard x-ray.\n  This is quite rare though.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>There’s no blood test for osteoarthritis\n  but they can be used to rule out other conditions</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t</section>\\r\\n\\t<section\n  id=\\\"treatment\\\" class=\\\"gray\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"row\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\"><h2>Treatment</h2></div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"col-xs-12\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>There’s no cure for osteoarthritis as yet,\n  but there are a number of treatments that can help ease symptoms and reduce the\n  chances of your arthritis becoming worse.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img src=\\\"/uploads/images/img06.png\\\"\n  alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-right\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<h3>Drugs for osteoarthritis of the\n  knee</h3>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Painkillers (analgesics)</strong> help with pain\n  and stiffness but they don’t affect the arthritis itself and won’t repair the damage\n  to your joint.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Painkillers are best used\n  occasionally when you’re in pain or when you’re likely to be exercising.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Paracetamol\n  is usually the best and most well-tolerated painkiller, but make sure you take the\n  right dose because many people take too little – try 1 g (usually 2 tablets) 3 or\n  4 times a day. You can buy them from your chemist or supermarket.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Combined\n  painkillers (e.g. co-codamol, co-dydramol) contain paracetamol and a second codeine-like\n  drug, so they may be helpful for more severe pain. Because they’re stronger than\n  painkillers, they’re more likely to cause side-effects such as dizziness and constipation.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Non-steroidal\n  anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs),</strong> for example ibuprofen or naproxen, may\n  be recommended if inflammation is contributing to your pain and stiffness.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>NSAIDs\n  can sometimes have side-effects, but your doctor will take precautions to reduce\n  the risk of these. They may suggest the lowest effective dose for the shortest possible\n  time and prescribe another drug called a proton pump inhibitor to help protect your\n  stomach from digestive problems.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>NSAIDs also carry a slightly\n  increased risk of a heart attack or stroke, so your doctor will be cautious about\n  prescribing them if there are other factors that increase your overall risk (e.g.\n  you smoke or you have circulation problems, diabetes, high blood pressure or high\n  cholesterol).</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory\n  creams and gels are a good option if you have trouble taking NSAID tablets.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Creams\n  and gels can be applied directly onto painful joints three times a day and there’s\n  no need to rub them in – they absorb through your skin on their own.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>They’re\n  extremely well tolerated because very little is absorbed into your bloodstream.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>You\n  can tell within a few days whether they’ll help with your pain.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img\n  class=\\\"pull-left\\\" src=\\\"/uploads/images/img12.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Capsaicin\n  cream</strong> is made from the pepper plant (capsicum) and is an effective and\n  well-tolerated painkiller.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Capsaicin cream\n  is only available on prescription and needs to be applied three times a day.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Most\n  people feel a warming or burning sensation when they first use it, but this generally\n  wears off after several days.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>The pain relief starts after\n  a few days and you should try it for at least two weeks before deciding if it’s\n  helped.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Stronger painkillers,</strong>\n  for example opioids/anti-inflammatories, may be prescribed if you have severe pain\n  and other medications don’t work well enough.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Stronger\n  painkillers are more likely to have side-effects, especially nausea, dizziness and\n  confusion, so you’ll need to see your doctor regularly and report any problems.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Some\n  opioids can be given as a plaster patch to wear on your skin, which can give pain\n  relief for a number of days.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Stronger painkillers are only\n  available on prescription.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Because these\n  treatments work in different ways, you can combine them for greater pain relief.\n  Ask your chemist or doctor for advice on safe combinations.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img\n  src=\\\"/uploads/images/img07.png\\\" alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-right\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Steroid\n  injections</strong> are sometimes given directly into a particularly painful knee\n  joint.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>The injections can start working\n  within a day or so and may improve pain for several weeks or months.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>They’re\n  mainly used for very painful osteoarthritis, for sudden attacks caused by shedding\n  calcium crystals and to help you through important events (such as a family wedding).</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Arthritis\n  Research UK has awarded a grant for the PROMOTE trial, a study into whether methotrexate,\n  a drug commonly used to treat rheumatoid arthritis, can be used to treat osteoarthritis\n  of the knee. Another trial is looking into whether a drug called spironolactone\n  is an effective treatment.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>If you have trouble opening childproof\n  containers, ask the pharmacist to put your drugs in a more suitable container. You\n  can also order a child-resistant closure card.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<h3>Other treatment\n  options</h3>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Applying warmth or cold</strong> to your knee\n  can relieve pain and stiffness.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Heat lamps\n  are popular, but a hot-water bottle or reheatable pad (available from most chemists)\n  are just as effective.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>An ice pack can also ease pain.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>Don’t\n  apply a hot or cold pad directly onto the skin.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Hyaluronic\n  acid injections,</strong> which help to lubricate your knee joint, are sometimes\n  given when steroid injections don’t work.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>You\n  may be given a single injection or a course of several injections.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>This\n  form of treatment isn’t approved by the National Institute for Health and Clinical\n  Excellence (NICE) and isn’t widely used because the evidence that it works isn’t\n  convincing.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img class=\\\"pull-left\\\" src=\\\"/uploads/images/img08.png\\\"\n  alt=\\\"\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Transcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation (TENS),</strong>\n  can be used for pain relief, although research evidence suggests that it doesn’t\n  work for everyone.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>A TENS machine is a\n  small electronic device that sends pulses to the nerve endings via pads placed on\n  the skin. The device produces a tingling sensation which is thought to modify the\n  pain messages sent to the brain.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>TENS machines are available\n  from pharmacies and other major stores, but a physiotherapist may be able to loan\n  you one to try before you decide to buy one.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Knee\n  braces</strong> are becoming more popular and more evidence to support their use\n  for osteoarthritis is emerging.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>There are\n  several types that can help to stabilise the kneecap and make it move correctly.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li>You\n  can buy knee braces from sports shops and chemists, but you should speak to your\n  doctor or physiotherapist first. They may also be able to provide braces or recommend\n  the best ones for you.</li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p><strong>Surgery</strong>\n  may be recommended if you have severe pain or mobility problems.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<h3>Surgery</h3>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>In\n  cases of advanced OA where surgery is called for, patients may also see a physical\n  therapist before surgery to discuss exercises that will be used just after surgery\n  and to begin practicing using crutches or a walker.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<img src=\\\"/uploads/images/img09.png\\\"\n  alt=\\\"\\\" class=\\\"pull-left\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<strong>Arthroscopy</strong>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Surgeons\n  can use an arthroscope (mentioned earlier) to check the condition of the articular\n  cartilage. They can also clean the joint by removing loose fragments of cartilage.\n  People have reported relief when doctors simply flush the joint with saline solution.\n  A burring tool may be used to roughen spots on the cartilage that are badly worn.\n  This promotes growth of new cartilage called fibrocartilage, which is like scar\n  tissue. This procedure is often helpful for temporary relief of symptoms for up\n  to two years.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<strong>Proximal Tibial Osteotomy</strong>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>OA\n  usually affects the side of the knee closest to the other knee (called the medial\n  compartment) more often than the outside part (the lateral compartment). OA in the\n  medial compartment can lead to bowing of the knee. As mentioned earlier, a bowlegged\n  posture places more pressure than normal on the medial compartment. The added pressure\n  leads to more pain and faster degeneration where the cartilage is being squeezed\n  together.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Surgery to realign the angles in the lower leg can\n  help shift pressure to the other, healthier side of the knee. The goal is to reduce\n  the pain and delay further degeneration of the medial compartment.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>One\n  procedure to realign the angles of the lower leg is called a proximal tibial osteotomy.\n  In this procedure, the upper (proximal)</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<strong>Artificial Knee\n  Replacement</strong>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>An artificial knee replacement is the ultimate\n  solution for advanced knee OA.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<p>Surgeons prefer not to put a\n  new knee joint in patients younger than 60. This is because younger patients are\n  generally more active and might put too much stress on the joint, causing it to\n  loosen or even crack. A revision surgery to replace a damaged prosthesis is harder\n  to do, has more possible complications, and is usually less successful than a first-time\n  joint replacement surgery.</p>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t</section>\\r\"\nposition: 1\n',NULL,'2015-02-18 12:22:52'),
	(16,'Rhinoart::PageContent',2,'update','1','---\nid: 2\npage_id: 1\nname: head\ncontent: ! \"\\t<header class=\\\"header\\\">\\r\\n\\t<h1 class=\\\"logo\\\"><a href=\\\"home.html\\\">Knee\n  Osteoarthritis</a></h1>\\r\\n\\t\\t<div class=\\\"holder container\\\">\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"row row-centered\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t<nav id=\\\"nav\\\" class=\\\"col-centered col-xs-12\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<div\n  class=\\\"navigation-block\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<span class=\\\"opener-nav\\\"></span>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<ul\n  class=\\\"navigation\\\">\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li class=\\\"active\\\"><a href=\\\"#definition\\\">Definition</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a\n  href=\\\"#prevalence\\\">Prevalence</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a href=\\\"#risk\\\">Risk\n  factors</a></li>\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a href=\\\"#symptoms\\\">Symptoms</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a\n  href=\\\"#diagnostic\\\">Diagnostic</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t<li><a href=\\\"#treatment\\\">Treatment</a></li>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</ul>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t</nav>\\r\\n\\t\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t\\t</div>\\r\\n\\t</header>\\r\\n\"\nposition: 2\n',NULL,'2015-02-18 12:22:52'),
